The reflectivity code consist of 2 executables: (1) axitra computes the Green's
function in the frequency domain for 5 double couples + isotropic source, at 
each receiver and for each source. (2) convm convolves these Green's function
by the appropriate source time function's, and for the chosen mechanism. The 
output are the seismograms in the time domain.

To compile the executables, you need first to build the fortran source files
with the C preprocessor, from the suffixed .F files. This allows to 
build different fortran source files with different options (ex single/double 
precision, storage/non storage of bessel function, etc...). You need
the C compiler if you decide to use the Lamont AH format.
If you don't have the C preprocessor or a C compiler to compile the local one,
(sfpp.c), the directory DEFAULT contains a default version of the fortran 
source files which may be compiled without the C compiler.

The option used to build the DEFAULT directory were:
- VERSION=STD (double precision)
- OUTPUT=BIN (Green's fucntions are stored in a binary  format)
- BESSEL=BSTO (store the value of the bessel function)
- BROUT=HARWELL
- AXES=RTV
- FORMAT=DUM (simple binary format for seismograms)
- LIBAH=

TO COMPILE
----------
- edit the Makefile,
- set the compiler(s) name according to your system
   (C compiler is used only to compile the sfpp preprocessor if you don't
    have a C preprocessor, and to compile the Lamont AH-IO library if you
    want the seismograms in AH format)
- set the different options you want to build the fortran source files,
  (*.F -> *.f)
- If you do not have a C preprocessor, set the preprocessor name to sfpp in the
   CPP macro name, then compile sfpp.c by typing "make sfpp",
- type make source to build the source files. The source.F files are 
  write-protected, you should not have to modify them. Modify the *.f,*.inc 
  files instead,
- Adjust the parameters in "parameter.inc" (see below) and in convm.f
  then type "make all" to produce the executables,
- "make clean" removes the object files, "make cleanall" removes also the 
  *.f files

axitra is then ready to run. The different data files are:
(1) input for axitra:
- "axi.data" +  file giving station coordinates + file giving sources 
  coordinates
(2) output from axitra:
- axi.head (parameters + information about convergence)
- axi.res  (binary transfert function)
or 
- axi.res (ascii file containing inform. + transfert functions)
(3) input for convm:
- axi.res (+ axi.head) + source info file
- axi.hist (time history + source parameters for each source)

!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! ATTENTION !!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
The sources/receivers are sorted by axitra according to increasing depth.
The reordering is done both in the receiver description file and in 
the seismogram file. Check the header (axi.head or axi.res) for the new ordering.
Same thing for the sources, but it is less crucial since they are indexed.

PARAMETERS (file "parameter.inc" and "axi.data")
------------
	The parameters defined in the file "parameter.inc" are the following:
- ncp=max number of layers
- nsp=max number of sources
- nrp=max number of receiver
- nkmax= If you have chose to store the bessel functions (which do not depend 
  upon the frequency), nkmax values will be stored for the first nkmax radial 
  wavenumber, if the number of iteration is larger than nkmax, the bessel 
  functions are recomputed each time for those nkmax+... iterations. This 
  value depends on the available memory and the convergence rate. 
  You can try to run the null frequency only to have a rough idea of
  how long it takes. Set nkmax to 3/2*number_of_iteration_for_freq=0 should be 
  ok if you don't compute too high frequencies (the higher the frequency, the 
  slower the convergence). (ps: You really save a lot of time by storing the 
  bessel functions)
- ikmin=min number of iterations

The parameters defined in "axi.data" are:
(1) in the namelist:
- nc=number of layer
- nfreq=number of frequency to compute
- tl=time length of the seismogram (sec)
- aw=coefficient for frequency imaginary part, omega=(2*pi*freq, aw*pi/tl)
- nr=number of receiver
- ns=number of sources
- xl=medium periodicity (m or km, be consistent with the other variables)
- ikmax=max number of iteration, generate an error message if overpassed
- uconv=convergence criteria, should not be too small in order to insure
  the convergence (>1.e-5)
- sourcefile=source description file
- statfile=receiver description file

(2) in free format and for each layer:
- thickness (or depth of the upper interface), vp, vs, rho, qp,qs
  If you specify the upper interface depth, it must be set to 0. for the
  free surface. rho must be consistent with the length unit (m or km)

DESCRIPTION FILES + AXI.HIST
---------------------------
in free format, 

for the receivers:
- x,y,z

for the sources:
- source_index, x, y, z

for the file AXI.HIST, 2 possibilities depending on the data you chose to
give: moment or displacement+width+length:
- source_index, moment, strike, dip, rake, 0., 0., t0
or
- source_index, disp , strike, dip, rake, width, length, t0

  If you want a null contribution for a given source, just set 
  the corresponding  moment (resp disp) to zero

AXIS CONVENTION
---------------
The convention for the axis is:
x=north, y=east, z=upward.
This convention is different in the computation where the vertical axis is 
positive downward. 
For the seismograms, depending on the option you choose, x is north 
(resp. radial), y is east (resp. tang) z is positive upward.



NOTE FOR THE AH FORMAT
----------------------
If you use the AH XDR format for the seismograms, convm does a little
bit more than for the single binary format. When convolving, it looks for
an AH header named head.ref. If it finds it, it uses it to set the event
 origin time. Besides, assuming that you used km coordinates in axitra,
it converts the station coordinates in lat/lon in the new AH header.

LIMITATIONS/NOTES
------------------
-Since the programs uses an horizontal wavenumber decomposition,
the only geometry not allowed is to put the receivers and the sources 
at the same depth. 
-The convergence rate depends in part on the depth difference between source 
  and receiver, the closer they are, the longer the convergence is.
- In some (rare) cases, the program may generate an underflow error when 
  computing the term "exp(-i*gamma*(z-zref)) where z may be
  the receiver or source depth, zref  the source or layer depth. This
  may occurs when you compute very high frequencies (KHz). A solution
 in that case is to incorporate a new artificial layer between z and zref
to reduce the (z-zref) term.
- An artificial vertical plane wave may be (rarely) seen when the source is
close to the free surface and when you look at regional distances. This
wave is seen only on the terms involving the J0 bessel function. It 
decreases very quickly as a function of the source depth but has no
geometrical spreading (it is a plane wave) and may be visible at the
beginning of the seismogram. There is nothing yet to do to remove
it completly. Using a recipy given by Bob Herrmann, the horizontal
wavenumbers are given a small fractional part, this reduces greatly
the effet of this spurious plane wave.
